definition.value: a digestive system AE that has an abnormal communication between the gallbladder and another organ or anatomic site.
a digestive system AE that has blockage of the normal flow of the contents of the gallbladder.
a gastrointestinal perforation AE that occurs in the stomach wall.
a gastrointestinal disoder AE that has an abnormal communication between any part of the gastrointestinal system and another organ or anatomic site.
a gastric AE that has an incomplete paralysis of the muscles of the stomach wall resulting in delayed emptying of the gastric contents into the small intestine.
a digestive system AE that has a narrowing of the lumen of the ileum.

a digestive system AE that has a rupture in the jejunal wall.
a digestive system AE that has a narrowing of the lumen of the jejunum.
a digestive system AE that has a circumscribed, inflammatory and necrotic erosive lesion on the mucosal surface of the jejunum.
a digestive system AE that has inadequate absorption of nutrients in the small intestine. Symptoms include abdominal marked discomfort, bloating and diarrhea.
a digestive system AE that has blockage of the normal flow of the contents in the stomach.
a digestive system AE that has a rupture in the wall of the extrahepatic or intrahepatic bile duct.
a digestive system AE that has an abnormal communication between the rectum and another organ or anatomic site.
a digestive system AE that has a rupture in the rectal wall.
a digestive system AE that has a narrowing of the lumen of the rectum.
a digestive system AE that has a circumscribed, inflammatory and necrotic erosive lesion on the mucosal surface of the rectum.

a digestive system AE that has a rupture in the small intestine wall.

a digestive system AE that has an abnormal communication between the jejunum and another organ or anatomic site.

an eye AE that has dryness of the cornea and conjunctiva.
an eye AE that has a sudden or brief burst of light.
an eye AE that has an individual seeing spots before their eyes. The spots are shadows of opaque cell fragments in the vitreous humor or lens.
an eye AE that has an inability to see clearly in dim light.
an eye AE that has a small laceration of the retina, this occurs when the vitreous separates from the retina. Symptoms include flashes and floaters.
an eye AE that has pathological retinal blood vessels that adversely affects vision.
an eye AE that has blood extravasation into the vitreous humor.
an eye AE that has excessive tearing in the eyes; it can be caused by overproduction of tears or impaired drainage of the tear duct.
an eye AE that has involvement of the optic nerve (second cranial nerve).
an eye AE that has involvement of the sclera of the eye.
an ear AE that has dizziness, imbalance, nausea, and vision problems.
